What is
Pycon 2018?

PyCon Philippines is a volunteer-run, not-for-profit conference centered around the Python Programming language.

The goal of the conference is to provide a venue where the Python programming language and surrounding technologies can be explored, discussed and exercised.

Python Software Foundation (PSF)
The mission of the Python Software Foundation is to promote, protect, and advance the Python programming language, and to support and facilitate the growth of a diverse and international community of Python programmers. The majority of the PSF's work is focused on empowering and supporting people within the Python community. The PSF has active grant programs that support sprints, conferences, meet ups, user groups, and Python development efforts all over the world. In addition, the PSF underwrites and runs PyCon US, the primary Python community conference. Being part of the PSF means being part of the Python community. Recently we changed the PSF to an open membership organization, so that everyone who uses and supports Python can join. To learn more, visit https://www.python.org/psf/membership.

Code of Conduct

PyCon PH is a community conference intended for collaboration in the developer community.

We value the participation of each member of the Python community and want all attendees to have an enjoyable and fulfilling experience. Accordingly, all attendees are expected to show respect and courtesy to other attendees throughout the conference and at all conference events, whether officially sponsored by Python.PH or not.

To make clear what is expected, all delegates/attendees, speakers, exhibitors, organizers and volunteers at any PyCon event are required to conform to the following Code of Conduct. Organizers will enforce this code throughout the event.

The long version

Harassment includes offensive verbal comments related to gender, gender identity and expression, sexual orientation, disability, physical appearance, body size, race, religion, status, sexual images in public spaces, deliberate intimidation, stalking, following, harassing photography or recording, sustained disruption of talks or other events, inappropriate physical contact, and unwelcome sexual attention.

Participants who are asked to stop any harassing behavior are expected to comply immediately.

Be careful in the words that you choose. Remember that sexist, racist, and other exclusionary jokes can be offensive to those around you. Excessive swearing and offensive jokes are not appropriate for PyCon.

Exhibitors in the expo hall, sponsor or vendor booths, or similar activities are also subject to the anti-harassment policy. In particular, exhibitors should not use sexualized images, activities, or other material. Booth staff (including volunteers) should not use sexualized clothing/uniforms/costumes, or otherwise create a sexualized environment.

If a participant engages in harassing behavior, the conference organizers may take any action they deem appropriate, including warning the offender or expulsion from the conference with no refund. If you are being harassed, notice that someone else is being harassed, or have any other concerns, please contact a member of conference staff immediately.

Conference staff can be identified by t-shirts/special badges/head sets.

Conference staff will be happy to help participants contact hotel/venue security or local law enforcement, provide escorts, or otherwise assist those experiencing harassment to feel safe for the duration of the conference. We value your attendance.

We expect participants to follow these rules at all conference venues and conference-related social events.

Erika Fille Legara Ph.D.

Introduction to the Natural Language Processing with Python

10:45AM - 11:45AM

Albertus Kelvin

Primarily, this talk is intended to the enthusiasts of NLP who would like to grasp the basic concepts of NLP and the way of implementing NLP tasks using Python. Therefore, this tutorial does not only give the concept of NLP, but it also provides the practical side by using Python programming language. The Python programming language can do the basic tasks of NLP, but it can not handle the standard task of NLP. Therefore, a special library called the Natural Language Toolkit (NLTK) is needed to solve such problem. This library provides some functions, wrappers, and the corpora samples that could be used to support the NLP research. By the end of this talk, hopefully the audience could get some insights on the basic concepts of NLP. Moreover, they could apply the NLTK for assisting their works.

Python and the Blockchain Revolution

2:00PM - 3:00PM

Johnny Estilles

Though the blockchain space continues is continually expanding, its knowledge and understanding throughout the technical community and the general public has not kept pace. The goal of this talk is to: - Increase awareness of blockchain - Explain the technical aspects of blockchain - Explore potential use cases for blockchain beyond cryptocurrencies - Encourage the development of blockchain projects in Python

Put your analysis to a web app using Dash

3:00PM - 4:00PM

Jolly Ann Bilad

We aim to use Dash in providing web apps for our analysis. This is important because analysts also aim to showcase their analysis to audiences. In this project, Twitter data is the one we'll use. Simple analyses and basic plotly graphs will be enough to show how to use Dash in the most basic level. We're only be using line graphs and distributions from the plotly package in python.

Snack Break

4:00PM - 4:15PM

Write Clean and Maintainable Code with Service Objects

4:15PM - 5:15PM

Mitchel Cabuloy

Code architecture is hard. Make it easier by using service objects! It's a design pattern that decouples your business logic from everything else. No more mixing presentation logic with business logic. No more putting business logic in model methods. With service objects, writing and testing features has never been easier. Come and learn how to use this nifty little design pattern. You'll see the benefits of service objects, how to write them, how to test them, and how it all fits in when used on a real-world project.

Designing Reliable, Scalable & Secure Data-Intensive Python Apps

5:15PM - 6:15PM

Joshua Arvin Lat

Designing and building data-intensive systems require proper planning and execution to effectively analyze and process large amounts of data. We'll discuss different techniques and technologies used to meet scalability, performance, and reliability requirements in your production Python applications.

Healthy Python: Applying Python in Healthcare

3:00PM - 4:00PM

Niño Eclarin

The talk will mainly focus on the following points. - What are the different challenges in the healthcare sector - How to identify if python is the right tool for those problems - What are the tools/resources that python provides that can help solve these challenges. Will introduce several tools/libraries/project available in python for several healthcare use cases - Identify execution plans when using these tools, will discuss the implications of using python vs the expectation of the intended stakeholders in health care - Future assumptions and directions for people who want to step into healthcare using python and similar technologies

Containing bugs.python.org

4:15PM - 5:15PM

Mark Mangoba

bugs.python.org, a tracker maintained by the Python community and for the community. For years, since 2011 it has helped the community triage thousands of issues. The trackers vintage infrastructure has needed a refactor to keep up with today’s standards. Python Community Member and Red Hat Engineer, Maciej Szulik and PSF IT Manager Mark Mangoba have been working on deploying bugs.python.org to Red Hat Open Shift, https://github.com/python/bpo-builder for the past year. Mark will be going over Red Hat Open Shifts benefits and how the community can contribute to its Infrastructure.

Resurrecting the dead with deep learning

11:00AM - 12:00PM

Aditthya Ramakrishnan

People have used these techniques to generate literature in the style of dead writers and poets like Nietzsche, Shakespeare and Robert Frost., Generate beautiful AI composed music inspired by the likes of Mozart, Beethoven and Bach., Generate lyrics and rap by training on Lennon-McCartney & Hamilton songs respectively.

Data visualization in Python

3:00PM - 4:00PM

Brian Baquiran

Thanks to its accessibility, and the availability of powerful toolkits for statistical and scientific computing, Python is now the most popular language for data science and machine learning. Data visualization is an important part of the data science process. It is vital both in the early stages, when exploring a new dataset, and in the final stages when communicating findings and results to your audience. This talk will cover several different data visualization tools in Python, explore their use cases, and how to use them effectively.

Video editing with MoviePy

Sony Valdez

Using MoviePy, we will create short clips of videos. We will demonstrate how to do this programmatically or from a different Python library. We will create GIFs that are perfect for memes. Jupyter support will also be demonstrated.

Walkthrough cpython 3.6 source code

2:00PM - 4:00PM

Prashanth Raghu

This talk will be an introduction to cpython from a source code level. We will walk through the source code of python from the parser, compiler, assembler and interpreter phases. We will also understand the design of the garbage collector, memory allocator from a source code perspective. We shall also explore the different design philosophies of cpython. There will be special emphasis on python objects such as lists, tuples, dictionaries etc and their design internals. This talk is for people who are interested to explore how cpython works internally.
